    (5,"medium","Reserved constituency ఒక general candidate contest చేయగలదా? / Can a general category candidate contest from a reserved constituency?",
     "Yes freely","No — SC reserved seats: only SC candidates can contest; ST reserved seats: only ST candidates can contest; general candidates cannot contest from reserved seats","Both can contest","Only some general candidates","b",
     "Reserved constituencies: SC reserved seats — only Scheduled Caste candidates can contest (and all voters vote); ST reserved seats — only Scheduled Tribe candidates can contest. General category candidates CANNOT contest from reserved seats. / Reserved constituency: only SC/ST candidates can contest from SC/ST reserved seats."),

    # Section 6: 42nd & 84th Amendments (8)
    (6,"easy","42nd Amendment 1976 ఏ change చేసింది Delimitation context? / What change did 42nd Amendment 1976 make in Delimitation context?",
     "Created Delimitation Commission","Froze total number of Lok Sabha + State Assembly seats until 2001 census — also froze constituency delimitation","Abolished Delimitation","Doubled seats","b",
     "42nd Constitutional Amendment Act 1976: froze (1) total number of Lok Sabha seats; (2) total number of State Assembly seats; and (3) constituency boundaries — all until first census after 2001. / 42nd Amendment 1976: seats + boundaries frozen until 2001 census."),
    (6,"medium","42nd Amendment seat freeze reason ఏమిటి? / What was the reason for the 42nd Amendment seat freeze?",
     "No reason","Prevent states with higher population growth from gaining more seats; incentivize family planning — penalise high-population growth","Only cost reason","Courts demanded it","b",
     "42nd Amendment seat freeze reason: prevent states with higher population growth from gaining more Lok Sabha seats at the expense of states that successfully controlled population growth (especially South Indian states). Incentivize family planning. / 42nd Amendment freeze: prevent high-population states gaining seats; incentivize family planning."),
    (6,"easy","84th Amendment 2001 ఏ extension చేసింది? / What extension did 84th Amendment 2001 make?",
     "Extended till 2011 census","Extended seat freeze until first census after 2026 (next: 2031)","Made freeze permanent","Ended the freeze","b",
     "84th Constitutional Amendment Act 2001: extended the seat freeze until the first census to be taken after 2026. India's next census is expected ~2031, after which delimitation will be done. / 84th Amendment 2001: extended freeze until first census after 2026."),
    (6,"hard","Seat freeze ని South Indian states ఎందుకు support చేస్తాయి? / Why do South Indian states support the seat freeze?",
     "They oppose freeze","South Indian states (Kerala, Tamil Nadu, Karnataka, AP, Telangana) successfully implemented family planning — if seats were reallocated based on current population, they would LOSE seats to more populous North Indian states","No view on freeze","All states oppose freeze","b",
     "South Indian states support the seat freeze: they have lower population growth rates due to successful family planning. If Lok Sabha seats were reallocated based on current population, these states would LOSE seats to northern states with higher populations. Seat freeze protects their representation. / South Indian states: support freeze; would lose seats if reallocated by current population."),
    (6,"medium","Seat freeze ని North Indian states ఎందుకు oppose చేస్తాయి? / Why do North Indian states oppose seat freeze?",
     "They support freeze","Higher population = should have more representation; north Indian states (UP, Bihar, MP, Rajasthan) have larger populations — current seat freeze underrepresents them","No view","They don't oppose","b",
     "North Indian states (UP, Bihar, MP, Rajasthan) have larger populations and thus argue for more seats — they are underrepresented under the current seat freeze. They generally favour delimitation based on current population. / North Indian states: oppose freeze; current allocation underrepresents their larger populations."),
    (6,"easy","Next Delimitation after seat freeze ఎప్పుడు? / When is the next Delimitation after the seat freeze?",
     "Already done 2021","After 2031 census (first census after 2026)","2025","Only after constitutional amendment","b",
     "Next Delimitation: after the first census taken after 2026 — India's next census expected around 2031. This will be the 5th Delimitation Commission. Women's 33% reservation will also be implemented from this delimitation. / Next Delimitation: after 2031 census (first census after 2026)."),
    (6,"hard","Delimitation 2031 census ఏ significant changes expect? / What significant changes are expected in Delimitation based on 2031 census?",
     "No changes expected","Major changes: (1) Seat reallocation based on population shifts; (2) 33% women's reservation (106th Amendment 2023) implementation; (3) Significant boundary changes","Only minor changes","Only SC/ST changes","b",
     "Delimitation after 2031 census will involve: (1) Reallocation of Lok Sabha seats based on current population (possibly more seats to north India); (2) Implementation of 33% women's reservation (106th Amendment 2023 — triggered by post-2026 census delimitation); (3) Comprehensive constituency boundary changes. Major political implications. / 2031 census delimitation: seat reallocation + women's 33% reservation."),
    (6,"medium","106th Amendment 2023 నియోజకవర్గ పరిమితితో ఎలా connect అవుతుంది? / How does 106th Amendment 2023 connect to Delimitation?",
     "No connection","106th Amendment: 33% women's reservation in Lok Sabha + State Assemblies — BUT effective only after delimitation following first census after 2026; Delimitation Commission will designate reserved seats for women","Already effective","Only state issue","b",
     "106th Constitutional Amendment 2023 (Nari Shakti Vandan Adhiniyam): provides 33% reservation for women in Lok Sabha and State Assemblies. BUT the reservation comes into effect only after delimitation following the first census after 2026. So the 5th Delimitation Commission (post-2031 census) will implement this. / 106th Amendment + Delimitation: women's 33% reservation effective only after post-2026 census delimitation."),

